JOHANNESBURG &#8211; South Africa&#8217;s rand was barely changed in early trade on Thursday, a day after Finance Minister Pravin Gordhan targeted the wealthy with tax hikes, in a bid to rein in the budget deficit.At 0730 GMT, the rand traded at 12.9625 per dollar, close to its New York close on Wednesday.In fixed income, the yield on the benchmark government bond due in 2026 firmed, shedding 7.5 basis points to 8.690%.&#8220;ZAR (rand) shrugs off budget speech,&#8221; NKC African Economics said in a morning note, referring to the budget, adding that the impact of the budget on consumer inflation and interest rates was largely neutral.&#8220;In emerging capital markets, conditions for inflows into emerging markets remained favourable as US treasuries prices were stable.&#8221;On the bourse, stocks opened lower, with the JSE securities exchange&#8217;s Top-40 index down 0.48%.